Their removal gave 25 million acres of land \"to white settlement and to slavery,\"","languageCode":"und","legacyId":0,"id":"18335065|3507413319301219"},{"platformId":"503055433070371_3486156691426882","platform":"Facebook","date":"2020-01-20 17:12:11","updated":"2022-01-06 21:05:58","type":"status","message":"Reflections from the Dallas Women’s March (long post)... If you had 60-90 seconds to explain the MMIW crisis to a stranger, what would you say? Yesterday while walking to my car, a woman stopped me who appeared to be with the counter-protest group that many of us saw towards the end of the march. She introduced herself to me as a “proud conservative woman,” but wanted to know more about MMIW and exactly who was in charge of taking care of the issue and pursuing these cases. She had heard about the issue but was generally unfamiliar with the specifics. I had to think quick because we were in passing. First, I explained the huge problem with the many jurisdictions involved when these crimes happen - there are continual conflicts between the feds, tribal entities and state/local law enforcement around who has the jurisdiction to pursue these cases, especially on tribal lands. I told her about our relative Mary Lyons, and Lieutenant Gov. Peggy Flanagan of Minnesota and how they helped get a task force passed into law to address this specific problem, and that she should look it up. I told her that due to jurisdiction conflicts, families, communities and organizations end up being the ones taking on the investigative work to find their loved ones instead of the police. Then she asked, “I’ve heard many of these women are being sex trafficked, is that true?” - unfortunately, yes, I said. I then chose to elaborate on the fact that pipeline construction has a direct correlation with violence against Native women and girls, especially on reservations. I told her about man camps and dirty energy projects. We had to part ways and she thanked me genuinely for talking with her, and I thanked her for asking. It was nice to find that what I initially thought could have been an uncomfortable encounter turned into an opportunity to educate. Did you have any conversations with strangers yesterday at the march? How would you describe the MMIW crisis in less than 2 minutes? (I want to also extend a special thank you to our ambassador Jodi Voice Yellowfish for organizing the Native presence at the march and giving us the opportunity to raise awareness about this and other important issues!) - 03:44:25","updated":"2022-01-06 21:03:55","type":"link","title":"This is a re-share of a post","description":"Jade Wagon \uD83C\uDF39\uD83D\uDC94\n\nRIVERTON, Wyo. — A woman missing since early January was found dead late last week, authorities told multiple news outlets on Monday.\n\nJade Wagon, 23, was last seen on Jan. 2. Authorities had recently asked for help finding Wagon, according to a Riverton Police Department Facebook post last week. \n\nOnline news outlet County 10 first reported that Fremont County Coroner Mark Stratmoen confirmed that Wagon was found dead but said he otherwise provided no other details. Neither Stratmoen nor his chief deputy responded to requests for comment from the Casper Star-Tribune by press time Monday.\n\nFremont County Chief Deputy Coroner Erin Ivie also confirmed the death to K2 on Monday. \n\nIn a Facebook post on Sunday morning, Rep. Andi Clifford, D-Fort Washakie, gave her \"sincerest condolences to the family and friends\" of Wagon, a Northern Arapaho tribal member with two children. \n\n\"She was loved by many,\" Clifford said in her post. \"May the Creator comfort everyone during this difficult time.\"\n\nAuthorities have so far not provided any details, including when and where she was found, how she died or if foul play is suspected. \n\nNews of the discovery of Wagon's body first appeared on social media over the weekend. Despite asking for the public's help in finding Wagon, authorities have made no public announcement saying they found Wagon, as of 5 p.m. Monday. \n\nThe Bureau of Indian Affairs' Wind River Police Department is leading the investigation, according to Riverton Police Department spokesman Capt. Todd Byerly. He said he could not confirm any other details. \n\nWind River Police Department Chief Tony Larvie did not respond to two requests for comment on Monday.  \n\nWagon's death comes as the missing and murdered Indigenous women crisis continues to garner more attention. While the true scope of the problem is unclear, Indigenous people face higher rates of sexual and physical violence.\n\nThe movement to address the problem has gained momentum and increased awareness nationally and in Wyoming. In Wyoming, that’s meant forming a task force to examine the problem and come up with potential solutions.\nLawmakers are also set to take up legislation this session that would require better data collection, better cooperation between agencies when investigating these cases and improved training.\n\nWagon’s death isn’t her family’s first experience with the missing and murdered Indigenous person crisis. Last year, on Jan. 5, Jocelyn Watt — Wagon’s oldest sister — was shot and killed in a double homicide in her Riverton home along with another, Rudy Perez. Both were 30 years old. No arrests have been made.\n\nFamily, friends and law enforcement held a news conference last September, where they asked for anyone with information about the homicides to come forward.\n\nWagon’s death also follows the death of Selena Not Afraid — a 16-year-old Native American teen from Montana — which has received widespread attention as another example of missing and murdered Indigenous people.\n\nSelena was last seen at a rest stop in Big Horn County, Montana, on New Year’s Day. She was found dead 20 days later less than a mile from there. More than 1,000 attended her funeral over the 22:54:06","updated":"2022-01-06 21:05:58","type":"photo","message":"Martin Luther King & American Indian Civil Rights   Few know that Dr. Martin Luther King was a great freedom fighter for American Indians and the horrific mistreatment to them by the U.S. government. King wrote in his 1963 book \"Why We Can't Wait” which outlined the historic injustices inflicted on American Indian people:   . . . . . . . . . . . . . . \"Our nation was born in genocide when it embraced the doctrine that the original American, the Indian, was an inferior race. Even before there were large numbers of Negroes on our shores, the scar of racial hatred had already disfigured colonial society. From the sixteenth century forward, blood flowed in battles of racial supremacy. We are perhaps the only nation which tried as a matter of national policy to wipe out its Indigenous population. Moreover, we elevated that tragic experience into a noble crusade. Indeed, even today we have not permitted ourselves to reject or feel remorse for this shameful episode. Our literature, our films, our drama, our folklore all exalt it.\" Unfortunately, these words still ring true to this day in so many respects. Dr. King was a fighter for all of the oppressed of this land. He assisted Native people in south Alabama in the late 1950s. At that time the Pouch Band of Creek Indians were completely desegregate schools in their area. Native children were allowed to ride school buses to previously all white schools, while dark-skinned Indian children from the same band were barred from riding the same buses. Tribal leaders, upon hearing of King's desegregation campaign in Birmingham, Ala., contacted him for assistance. He responded and through his intervention the problem was quickly resolved. At the 1964 March on Washington there was a Native American presence. Dr. King’s civil rights movement motivated the Native American rights movement of the 1960s. The Native American Rights Fund (NARF) was patterned after the NAACP's Legal Defense and Education Fund. By 1900 there were only 237,196 Native Americans left in the entire country, this from an original population that numbered in the tens of millions. King spoke out that the genocide of American Indians was \"national policy.\" As late as the 1890s the U.S. Congress was debating the outright military extermination of all remaining Native Americans. The reason this nefarious plan was not carried out was because it would be too Taking action together for truth telling and trust building that lead to racial healing for a more just and equitable future. . . . . . . . . . . . Our Project for Action: Arkikosa: Renaming Trinity River to Arkikosa in Dallas, Texas. Not changing the name but reclaiming back our namesake The Caddo Nation named the river “Arkikosa” that runs next to downtown Dallas. Today, the river is known as the Trinity River. “Arkikosa” creates an awareness involving underlying self-analysis to evaluate one’s place in a cultural landscape beyond day-to-day notions. By re-thinking the river’s visual identity, we will re-brand with a cultural and educational approach through consultancy. This re-branding will reflect our natural environment while simultaneously allowing us to explore how our urban environment affects our behaviors to reveal a new Texas truth. The idea to create an organic approach to re-naming a Dallas icon is fast growing. Imagine new urban multifaceted cultural living space concepts to enrich utopian visions. Utilizing elements from community and urbanization platforms helps inform the possibility of a multi-faceted and culturally-accurate community engagement hub. We are looking through the historical and cultural lens of changing the segment of the river that runs from far West Dallas to the Audubon to “Arkikosa.” We were asked years ago what we wanted to change while other cultural leaders were making changes to landmark sites and statues. We wanted to direct the narrative back to our American Indian people who were the original protectors of the land. Continuing the psycho-social journey that was ignited at Standing Rock, the “Water is Life” theme remains apparent in our visual transformation of the river, generating analogous parallels dealing with climate change and the preservation of the water that flows through the City of Dallas. This is the continuation of:Decolonize Dallas Installation, Fight for Climate Change. You take down Confederate statues; we will reclaim our namesake Arkikosa American Indian Heritage Day in Texas Indian Citizens Against Racial Exploitation Dallas Truth, Racial Healing & Transformation Christmas feeling and giving all year long. An estimated 3 to 4 million women are abused by their partners every year in the United States. When domestic violence occurs, women have limited options. Shelters do important work, but sadly, they are often underfunded and understaffed. And, in many cases, there is simply not a shelter nearby for women and their children to turn to. While there are over 3,800 animal shelters in America, there are only 1,500 shelters for victims of domestic violence. Necessities such as bras are hard to come by for women in shelters, as people rarely think to donate these items. Donating new sports bras in a variety of sizes and styles will make a huge difference in the lives of many women right in your very community.
